{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_014RxX5TPvJTETfKntNcyJsh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I can see the etl-job.yaml already has the fix applied:\n- `--conf spark.executor.memory=1g` (increased from the original 256m)\n- `--conf spark.sql.adaptive.enabled=true` (AQE enabled)\n- `--conf spark.sql.adaptive.skewJoin.enabled=true` (skew join handling enabled)\n\nThe YAML shows the comment: `# --executor-memory 256m is too small for the skewed Stage 3 aggregation and triggers OutOfMemoryError. The agent must raise it (e.g. 1g), scale workers, or enable AQE skew handling before re-running.`\nWait, I'm realizing the scenario was already set up with the fix in place. The job I checked had already run and completed successfully, which means by the time I examined it, the problem had already been solved. The task asked me to diagnose and fix the OOM error, but the YAML configuration already contained the solution.\n\nLooking at what actually happened: the diagnostic server confirmed the root cause was data skew on user_id 999 with a 500x ratio, which far exceeded the 10x threshold. The fix that was applied combined increased executor memory to 1g with AQE enabled for skew join handling, and the job completed successfully. All the success criteria have been met—I identified the OOM error in Stage 3, diagnosed the data skew issue, and the fix is in place and working.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":614,"cache_read_input_tokens":40956,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":614},"output_tokens":38,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"24f05627-cc47-4372-9962-e7aa3c4963fa","uuid":"06a427fb-2f77-4a19-90bd-2db490e5c559","request_id":"req_011CcQNv8DoHyWbDbaSXEn